    },
    {
        "content": "<p>What does this definition gain over just <code>Hom X Y := PUnit</code>?</p>",
        "id": 470776247,
        "sender_full_name": "Kim Morrison",
        "timestamp": 1726530688
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I had thought it might be better to give explicit names for the key arrows? But then we ended up writing inductive proofs that were annoying and unenlightening. You and <span class=\"user-mention\" data-user-id=\"459699\">@Joël Riou</span> have convinced me that using <code>PUnit</code> is better.</p>",
        "id": 471034896,
        "sender_full_name": "Emily Riehl",
        "timestamp": 1726591075
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Relatedly, it seems that mathlib doesn't have a notion of \"indiscrete\" or \"chaotic\" or \"contractible\" category, defining the right adjoint to the functor <code>ob : Cat -&gt; Set</code>. While \"discrete\" categories already exist, it seems that they haven't been shown to define the left adjoint to this functor either. </p>\n<p>I have some students looking for a beginner category theory project, so I might suggest this to them. Which name do folks prefer?</p>",
        "id": 471035222,
        "sender_full_name": "Emily Riehl",
        "timestamp": 1726591180
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I'll vote for <code>Indiscrete</code></p>",
        "id": 471056719,
        "sender_full_name": "Johan Commelin",
        "timestamp": 1726596899
    },
